Dragon Ball Dataset¶

Problem Definition¶

In the Dragon Ball universe, characters are defined by a wide range of attributes—from power levels and transformation abilities to battle experience and unique techniques. Despite the popularity of the series, there is no quantitative understanding of how these characteristics interact to influence outcomes such as fight results, power progression, and technique effectiveness. This project addresses the problem of extracting meaningful patterns from character data so that we can predict battle outcomes, estimate power levels, and ultimately provide tailored recommendations for character development.

Context¶

Dragon Ball is renowned for its intricate lore and dynamic character evolution. With a rich dataset that includes information on over 300 characters, hundreds of battles, and various attributes (e.g., training years, transformation levels, race, and techniques), there is a tremendous opportunity to apply different machine learning approaches. Whether it’s predicting if a character wins or loses a battle, estimating a character’s power level, or clustering characters into archetypes, this project uses a variety of methods (classification, regression, clustering, deep learning, and recommender systems) to explore the underlying relationships in the data. This EDA serves as the critical first step to identify which features matter most and how they interrelate within the complex, high-stakes world of Dragon Ball.

Objective¶

Discover Key Patterns:

  • Identify the most influential features (like power level, transformation, race, and battle history) that correlate with different outcomes.

Inform Model Selection:

  • Provide insights into which machine learning techniques might be best suited for tasks such as binary classification (win/loss prediction), continuous prediction (power level estimation), and unsupervised grouping (character archetypes).

Assess Data Quality:

  • Evaluate the completeness, distribution, and potential biases in the dataset (for example, ensuring that sparsity and missing values are understood and addressed).

Lay the Groundwork for Modeling:

  • Develop a deep understanding of the data’s structure that will drive the design of predictive models and recommendation systems—ultimately helping to answer questions like, “Which technique should a fighter learn?” or “How many battles before unlocking the next transformation?”

data power level Skewness:  3.792723305431414
data power level Kurtosis:  15.102000487440774

Power Level Insights

  • Mean Power Level: 17,028
  • Standard Deviation: 38,307 (very large spread)
  • Minimum: 5 (suggests weaker characters exist)
  • Maximum: 200,000 (suggests extremely powerful characters)
  • 75th Percentile: 10,000, meaning only 25% of characters have a Power Level higher than this.
  • Power Level is highly imbalanced, with a few characters having extreme values.
  • This is confirmed by the Skewness (3.79, positively skewed) → Data is right-skewed (mean > median), meaning a few characters have much higher power than the rest.
  • Kurtosis (15.10) → The distribution has heavy tails, meaning there are a few extreme values.

Categorical Insights

  • Most characters are Human (19 out of 68).
  • Males dominate (61 out of 68 characters).
  • Speed is highly imbalanced (most characters are "Fast").
  • Most characters have transformations (43 out of 68).

from plotly import graph_objects as go

race_trans_counts = data.groupby(['Race', 'Transformation']).size().reset_index(name='Count')

fig = go.Figure(go.Sankey(
    node=dict(
        pad=15,
        thickness=20,
        label=list(race_trans_counts['Race'].unique()) + list(race_trans_counts['Transformation'].unique())
    ),
    link=dict(
        source=[list(race_trans_counts['Race'].unique()).index(r) for r in race_trans_counts['Race']],
        target=[list(race_trans_counts['Transformation'].unique()).index(t) + len(race_trans_counts['Race'].unique()) for t in race_trans_counts['Transformation']],
        value=race_trans_counts['Count']
    )
))

fig.update_layout(title_text="Race to Transformation Flow", font_size=12)
fig.show()

EDA Post Analysis¶

Character Demographics:

  • Humans dominate the dataset (27.94%), followed by Androids (14.71%) and Aliens (11.76%). Males are the majority (89.71%), with Females making up only 10.29%. Diversity in characters is low, as most are either human or android.

Combat & Abilities

  • Most common Ki Blast techniques:
    • S.S. Deadly Bomber, Kamehameha, and Energy Wave (each appearing 6.25% of the time).
  • Melee Combat Style Distribution:
    • Android Strikes (15.79%) and Martial Arts (12.28%) are the most common techniques.
    • Angelic Martial Arts is rare (3.51%).
  • Special Attacks:
    • Majority have no special attack.
    • Few characters use Blue Cannonball and MAX Power Kamehameha.

Speed & Power

  • Speed Classification:
    • Fast (49.25%) is the most common.
    • Slow (41.79%) suggests many heavy combatants.
    • Average speed characters (8.96%) are rare.

Transformation Ability:

  • 63.24% of characters have no transformation.
  • 14.71% have a transformation, with only 5.88% achieving Super Saiyan.
  • Most Transformable Races: Saiyans, Namekians, and Half-Saiyans have the highest number of transformations.
  • Limited Transformations: Androids, Humans, and Aliens have minimal transformation abilities, with the majority having no transformations.
  • Super Saiyan & Beyond: Saiyans and Half-Saiyans dominate Super Saiyan transformations.

Data Preprocessing & Feature Engineering¶

Ordinal Encoding (Manual Mapping) Speed column

In [51]:

In [56]:
# Ensure Power Level is numeric
data['Power Level'] = pd.to_numeric(data['Power Level'], errors='coerce')

# Normalize Power Level to bring values to a 0-1 scale
data['Normalized_Power'] = (data['Power Level'] - data['Power Level'].min()) / (data['Power Level'].max() - data['Power Level'].min())
  # # scaled version of Power Level, ranging between 0 and 1.
  # ensures that all values are within a comparable range.
  # Used to balance calculations where raw Power Level values would be too large and dominate over other factors like Speed.

# Create Power Score (Weighted sum)
data['Power_Score'] = (data['Speed'] * 0.3) + (data['Normalized_Power'] * 0.7)
  # # raw strength metric
  # represents actual power without any modifications.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Conclusion

  • The exploratory data analysis (EDA) of the Dragon Ball dataset revealed key insights into character attributes, power levels, and rankings. The dataset contained various character traits such as race, power level, transformations, melee combat abilities, ki blasts, and speed, which were essential for understanding character strengths.

Key findings include:

  • Power Level Distribution: Some characters exhibited extreme power levels, indicating a right-skewed distribution.
  • Transformation Impact: Characters with multiple transformations tend to have significantly higher power levels.
  • Race and Strength: Saiyans dominate the dataset in terms of power and transformation capability, while other races tend to have lower power ceilings.
  • Speed & Power Relationship: Speed and power level seem to have a positive correlation, with higher-tier characters being both faster and stronger.
  • Ranking System: A ranking system was implemented based on Max Ki, categorizing characters from strongest to weakest.

The preprocessing steps included:

  • Encoding categorical variables such as race and transformation status.
  • Handling missing values, especially in power level estimates.
  • Creating engineered features, including power score and speed score.
  • Ranking characters based on their Max Ki and power stats.

Recommendations for Future Data Science Projects¶

This dataset provides a great foundation for various machine learning applications, including supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement learning techniques.

Supervised Learning Projects

  • Regression Analysis
    • Predict Power Levels based on race, experience, and transformations.
    • Estimate Battle Outcomes using combat attributes.
  • Classification Models
    • Battle Winner Prediction: Use logistic regression, decision trees, or neural networks to predict battle outcomes.
    • Transformation Recommendation: Given a character’s stats, suggest the best transformation.

Unsupervised Learning Projects

  • Character Clustering
    • Use K-Means or DBSCAN to group characters by fighting style, power, or transformation types.
    • Discover hidden archetypes, such as Tactical Fighters vs. Energy Blasters.
  • Anomaly Detection
    • Identify outliers in power levels or transformations.
    • Detect characters with extremely high battle efficiency compared to their peers.

Deep Learning Applications

  • Anime Scene Classification
    • Train a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to classify Dragon Ball fight scenes vs. non-fight scenes.
    • Use transfer learning (VGG16, ResNet) to automate scene detection.
  • Text-based Analysis
    • Use NLP models (BERT, GPT) to analyze Dragon Ball dialogues, detecting sentiment or key themes.

Time Series and Forecasting

  • Power Growth Over Time
    • Model how characters’ power levels evolve over different sagas using time series forecasting. Predict the next transformation or power spike based on past battles.
  • Battle Duration Prediction
    • Given a fight scenario, predict how long the battle will last.

Recommendation Systems

  • Binary Classification Recommender
    • "Should a character learn a technique (e.g., Kamehameha, Final Flash)?"
    • Use collaborative filtering with a binary classifier.
  • Multi-Class Recommendation
    • "Which transformation is best for a fighter?"
    • Recommend SSJ, SSJ2, SSJ3, Ultra Instinct, etc. based on attributes.
  • Regression-Based Recommender
    • Predict how many battles a character needs before unlocking a transformation.
